{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659532"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:11:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:11:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20869"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20869"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13744"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97550"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13744"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20869"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80150"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11595"},{"type":"tags","id":"12325"},{"type":"tags","id":"12693"},{"type":"tags","id":"12694"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33076"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33078"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97550"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHuman immunodeficiency virus (HIV) demonstrates distinct patterns of cellular tropism throughout the course of infection. These patterns are determined by the virus\u0027s ability to utilise specific cell surface molecules as coreceptors in conjunction with CD4.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best characterises the evolution of HIV coreceptor usage during disease progression?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["X4 strains predominate early and are replaced by R5 strains","R5 strains predominate early and X4 strains emerge later","R5X4 dual-tropic strains are consistently dominant throughout infection","Coreceptor usage remains stable with no tropism shift during infection","CCR5 usage increases as CD4+ T cell counts decline"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct characterisation is that \u003Cstrong\u003ER5 strains predominate early and X4 strains emerge later\u003C/strong\u003E in HIV infection. In approximately 90% of cases, R5 (M-tropic) strains that utilise the CCR5 coreceptor are the dominant viral population during acute infection and early in disease. These strains preferentially infect monocytes and macrophages. As the infection progresses, there is typically a gradual accumulation of X4 (T-tropic) strains that use the CXCR4 coreceptor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EX4 strains predominate early and are replaced by R5 strains\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the opposite of the actual pattern. R5 strains typically dominate early infection, not X4 strains.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ER5X4 dual-tropic strains are consistently dominant throughout infection\u003C/strong\u003E - While dual-tropic strains that can use both CCR5 and CXCR4 do exist, they are not consistently dominant throughout the course of infection.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoreceptor usage remains stable with no tropism shift during infection\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect as there is typically a shift from R5 to X4 tropism as the disease progresses.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECCR5 usage increases as CD4+ T cell counts decline\u003C/strong\u003E - The opposite occurs; CXCR4 usage (X4 strains) tends to increase as disease progresses and CD4+ counts decline.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe emergence of X4 strains later in infection is clinically significant because these viruses are particularly virulent. They can infect a broader range of T cells, including thymic T-cell precursors, leading to greater T-cell depletion and more rapid disease progression. This tropism shift is associated with accelerated progression to AIDS in many patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["HIV viral tropism is determined by coreceptor usage, with R5 strains using CCR5 and X4 strains using CXCR4.","R5 (M-tropic) strains predominate in early HIV infection and preferentially infect monocytes/macrophages.","X4 (T-tropic) strains emerge later in disease progression, preferentially infect T cells, and are associated with accelerated disease progression."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 6; pages 249-250."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80150"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20869"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80150"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-07T21:51:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-07T21:52:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13744"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97550"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11595"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diseases of the immune system","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":5,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:55:18+10:30","updat